Measuring the NPS (Net Promoter Score) in each course_day¶

In [9]:
def nps(answers):
    nps_grade = 0
    for grade in answers:
        if grade >= 9:
            nps_grade += 1
        elif grade <= 6:
            nps_grade -= 1   
    return round(nps_grade/len(answers)*100,2)

for n in range(0,len(data_relevant[data_relevant.course_day != 0].course_day.unique())):
    x = data_pivot[n]['NPS']
    print(f'Day {n+1} NPS was {nps(x.values)}')

Drawing a chart for each course_day showing the value counts for each grade.¶

my_cmap = plt.get_cmap("Blues")
for n in range(0,len(data_relevant[data_relevant.course_day != 0].course_day.unique())):
    plt.figure(figsize = (8,16))
    plt.subplot(len(data_relevant[data_relevant.course_day != 0].course_day.unique()),1,n+1)
    grNps = data_pivot[n]['NPS'].value_counts().sort_index(ascending = False)
    rescale = lambda y: (y - np.min(y)) / (np.max(y) - np.min(y))
    bars = plt.bar(x = grNps.index, height = grNps.values, color=my_cmap(rescale(grNps.values)))
    for bar in bars:
        yval = bar.get_height()
        plt.text(bar.get_x()+0.3, yval + 0.4, yval)
    plt.show()

3 NLP (natural language processing)¶

The way humans talk is not something comprehensible to a computer. Therefore, before applying computer-based algorithms, groupings, charts, etc. we need to convert data to a more "understandable", or "machine-friendly", form so that we get to process and analyze such data. This is where NLP comes in, combining linguistics with computer science, to transform words and sentences that we so commonly use in their infinite forms, to more neutral and common words, e.g. changing "eating" and "ate" to simply "eat".

3.1 Stopwords¶

Stopwords are defined as words that do not add any meaning to our sentences, such as the "as" in this sentece. It is common in NLP pipelines to remove such words before any processing. For this project, I'll be using NLTK's stopwords list.

Creating a nltk's stopwords list (data is pt-br so using portuguese stopwords)¶

In [19]:
pt_stopwords = set(stopwords.words('portuguese'))
#pt_stopwords

Function to tokenize sentences and remove the stopwords.¶

In [20]:
def remove_stopwords(sentence):
    word_tokens = word_tokenize(sentence)
 
    filtered_sentence = [w for w in word_tokens if not w.lower() in pt_stopwords]

    filtered_sentence = []

    for w in word_tokens:
        if w not in pt_stopwords:
            filtered_sentence.append(w)

    return filtered_sentence

Applying the function to our data and showing the output.¶

3.2 Removing punctuation and applying Lemmatisation¶

Depending on the processing used, we should our shouldn't remove punctuation. In this case, where I'm going to simply analyze words and word combinations, there is no need for punctuation so we are taking it out.

Lemmatisation, in linguistics, is a manner of extracting more "common" forms of words, grouping inflected words into a single item, called lemma. This way, we can group together words such as "ate" and "eating" under the single form "eat", as this item defines its' meaning.

Importing the necessary SpaCy portuguese pipeline (and downloading it, if needed)¶

In [23]:
#!spacy download pt_core_news_sm
In [24]:
import pt_core_news_sm
nlp = pt_core_news_sm.load()

Function to clean text by using regex (regular expressions) to remove punctuation and using Spacy to apply lemmatisation.¶

In [25]:
def clean_sentences(text):
    
    # Removes pontuação using regular expressions
    regex = re.compile('[' + re.escape(string.punctuation) + '\\r\\t\\n]')
    nopunct = regex.sub("", str(text))
    
    # Using SpaCy for lemmatisation
    doc = nlp(nopunct, disable = ['parser', 'ner'])
    lemma = [token.lemma_ for token in doc]
    return lemma

Applying function to the data.¶

3.3 Tokenization e removing outlier words¶

Tokenization, in lexical analysis, is the process of classifying a set of characters, segmenting them in such way that it would make sense for a natural language speaker. It could mean transforming an entire book in a set of chapters, or a paragraph in a set of phrases, depending on the process that will be used further down the NLP pipeline. In this case, we will simply split each phrase in a set of words.¶

In [29]:
answers_tokens = [item for items in data_pln_lower for item in items]
#answers_tokens

Some of our resulting words have unusual lenghts, since in the survey's answers people could insert links. As such, we'll remove any words above a set character length to avoid such invalid data. Some words got split into meaningless empty spaces, so we'll take care of that as well.¶

In [30]:
answers_notnull = pd.Series(answers_tokens)[pd.Series(answers_tokens).apply(lambda x: len(x)) > 2]

3.5 Bigrams¶

Bigrams, or more specifically a n-gram of n=2, is a form of statistical analysis of text that takes combinations of adjacent elements from a text, in our case words. This way we can visualize the most used two-word combinations from our data, giving some insight into the users' opinion.¶

Creating a Bigram finder from NLTK's package with our tokenized data¶

In [34]:
findBigrams = BigramCollocationFinder.from_words(answers_final.values)

Counting bigrams in the tokenized data¶

In [35]:

As a result of the project, three wordclouds will be created, to show the most used words, bigrams and tri-grams, giving insight to commonly expressed opinions by users in the survey's data.¶

Therefore, we could conclude, looking at the wordclouds, that something is up with our online video classes, seeing as 'video aula' and 'video_aula_melhorar', which mean 'improve video classes', appeared with certain frequency in all wordclouds. Also, the live classes and the teacher received some praise, because 'professor_saber_ensinar', which would somewhat translate to 'professor good at teaching', was one of the most frequent trigrams.¶

We could keep analyzing other subsets of data for more insights and even extract more data from other courses, but seeing as this is a simple demonstration, it should be enough for planning the next steps of our ficticious company. ;)¶
